{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b9425618-6ad5-4402-8861-12d1b08ffdae","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports via **ReportCrash**. Look in these locations:\n\n- **User-level:** `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n- **System-level:** `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS). They contain the stack trace, exception type, and thread state.\n\nYou can also:\n1. Open **Console.app** → sidebar → \"Crash Reports\"\n2. Run: `log show --predicate 'process == \"YourApp\"' --last 1h`\n\nFor richer dumps, set `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` before launching — but note this relies on `createdump` being present in the runtime pack, which NativeAOT doesn't include by default.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"91f39593-9ce0-4f62-a8dd-1297bf3ec68c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system generates crash reports automatically via ReportCrash. These are stored in specific directories.","outputTokens":320,"requestId":"DA13:349D35:22DB118:2693A8F:6A03D8A0"},"id":"5be02e96-4402-42c6-8dd5-fe9ace7b1563","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:49:29.961Z","parentId":"c5b1da9e-852d-4612-8b48-5a5ceed1ea59"}
